The accounting break-even is given at the point where the net profit is zero. This means that the operating cashflow is equal to the depreciation. Therefore, the formula can be re-written as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\frac{\text{D}-\text{T}\times \text{D}}{1-\text{T}}+\text{FC}}{\text{P}-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$

The cash break-even is the point wherein the operating cashflow is zero. Using the same formula in Step 1, we can rewrite it as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\frac{-(\text{T}\times \text{D})}{1-\text{T}}+\text{FC}}{\text{P}-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$
